USE CASE DRAFT: T1071 Application Layer Protocol



ATTACK DESCRIPTION
Adversaries may communicate with compromised systems using common application layer protocols such as HTTP or HTTPS to blend malicious traffic with normal network activity. Attackers often use web protocols to download tools, receive commands from a command-and-control (C2) server, exfiltrate data, or maintain persistence because web traffic is generally allowed through firewalls and proxies.

ATT&CK Mapping
Technique ID: T1071 
Technique name: Application Layer Protocol

Tactics:
- Command and Control(TA0011)
- Exfiltration(TA0010)


Detection Objective
- Identify suspicious use of HTTP/HTTPS by command-line utilities, scripting engines, or Living-off-the-Land Binaries (LOLBins) that may indicate command-and-control communication or malicious payload delivery.

Potential Data Sources
- Windows Security Logs
- Sysmon Event Logs(Event ID 1)
- Process Creation Events(Event ID 4688)
- Web Proxy Logs(if available)
- PowerShell Operational Logs
- DNS logs(if available)
- Firewall Logs(if available)

Detection Idea
- Monitor for processes initiating web requests using command-line tools and scripting engines that do not normally make external HTTP/HTTPS connections.

Examples of suspicious behavior:
- Powershell executing Invoke-WebRequest
- Powershell executing Invoke-RestMethod
- curl.exe downloading files from external websites
- certutil.exe downloading files from URLS
- bitsadmin.exe transferring files over HTTP/HTTPS
- mshta.exe reaching out to external websites
- Encoded Powershell commands containing URLS
- Repeated connections to unusual domains or IP addresses



Alert Concept: Suspicious Application Layer Protocol Detected

Trigger Condition: Execution of command-line utilities or scripting engines making external HTTP/HTTPS requests, especially when initiated by uncommon parent processes or involving file downloads.
Severity: HIGH  --> Critical if:
- PowerShell downloads a file from an external URL.
- certutil.exe, bitsadmin.exe, or curl.exe is used to retrieve content from the Internet.
- Encoded PowerShell commands contain URLs.
- Multiple download utilities are executed in a short time frame.
- The web request is followed by execution of a newly downloaded file.
- Communication occurs with an unknown or suspicious domain.


